ground_truth:
To use augmented reality in your Swift app, you can use the ARKit framework provided by Apple. ARKit is a powerful tool for creating immersive and interactive experiences that blend the virtual world with the real world. It provides a set of features such as motion tracking, scene understanding, and light estimation that makes it easy to create AR apps. Here are some steps to get started with AR development in iOS:

1. Set up your Xcode project: First, create a new Xcode project and select the "Augmented Reality App" template. This will automatically generate some starter code and assets to help you get started.

2. Add ARKit to your project: In order to use ARKit, you need to add it to your Xcode project. You can do this by going to your project settings and selecting "Capabilities", then turning on the "ARKit" option.

3. Build your AR scene: Next, you'll want to design your AR scene using ARKit's APIs. For example, you can use ARKit's scene understanding capabilities to detect objects and surfaces in the real world, and then place virtual objects on top of them. You can also use ARKit's motion tracking capabilities to track the user's movements and adjust the AR scene accordingly.

4. Run your AR app: Once you've built your AR scene, you can run your app on a device or simulator to see it in action. When running on a device, ARKit will use the device's cameras and sensors to create an accurate representation of the real world, and then overlay your virtual objects on top.

Here's an example of how to create a simple AR experience using Swift:

```
import UIKit
import SceneKit
import ARKit

class ViewController: UIViewController, ARSCNViewDelegate {

 @IBOutlet var sceneView: ARSCNView!

 override func viewDidLoad() {
 super.viewDidLoad()

 // Set the view's delegate
 sceneView.delegate = self

 // Show statistics such as fps and timing information
 sceneView.showsStatistics = true

 // Create a new scene
 let scene = SCNScene(named: "art.scnassets/ship.scn")!

 // Set the scene to the view
 sceneView.scene = scene
 }

 override func viewWillAppear(_ animated: Bool) {
 super.viewWillAppear(animated)

 // Create a session configuration
 let configuration = ARWorldTrackingConfiguration()

 // Run the view's session
 sceneView.session.run(configuration)
 }

 override func viewWillDisappear(_ animated: Bool) {
 super.viewWillDisappear(animated)

 // Pause the view's session
 sceneView.session.pause()
 }

 // MARK: - ARSCNViewDelegate

 func renderer(_ renderer: SCNSceneRenderer, didAdd node: SCNNode, for anchor: ARAnchor) {
 // This method is called when an anchor (i.e. a detected feature point or surface) is added to the scene
 guard let shipScene = SCNScene(named: "art.scnassets/ship.scn"),
 let shipNode = shipScene.rootNode.childNode(withName: "ship", recursively: false)
 else { return }

 // Position the ship at the location of the anchor
 shipNode.position = SCNVector3(anchor.transform.columns.3.x, anchor.transform.columns.3.y, anchor.transform.columns.3.z)

 // Add the ship to the scene
 node.addChildNode(shipNode)
 }

}
```

This example creates a simple AR experience that places a 3D model of a ship on top of detected surfaces in the real world. The code uses ARKit to track the user's movements and adjust the position of the ship accordingly. In addition, the `renderer(_:didAdd:for:)` method is called whenever a new anchor is added to the scene, allowing you to dynamically add content based on the user's environment.

There are also many third-party libraries and frameworks available for AR development in Swift, such as Vuforia, Wikitude, and EasyAR. These tools provide additional features and capabilities beyond what is offered by ARKit and can help you create more complex and advanced AR experiences.

